<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-015-127 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 468 026</DOCID><JOURNAL>San Jose Mercury News  Nov 9 1991 p1A(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Overloaded computers have city at dead end. (San Jose, CA)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hazle, Maline.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>San Jose, CA's 1989 Wang VS10000 minicomputer system using NissiTechnologies Inc's Munifax financial software is too overloaded todo the work it was installed to do.andP;  Municipal users, includingthe payroll, public works and redevelopment departments, complainthat the system is too slow and that entire groups can be lockedout when other groups use the system extensively.andP;  Problems withthe Munifax software include its proprietary nature and the factthat only Nissi employees, based in Vancouver, BC, can providesupport services.andP;  San Jose's system selection team chose Munifaxeven though its members knew how small Nissi is.andP;  They also choseWang in spite of the financial problems Wang has experienced since1985.andP;  The city chooses to stay with the system until at least1994 because of the cost involved in replacing it.andP;  Instead, Nissiis modifying its software to avoid shutout problems.andP;  Somehardware vendors are offering test equipment compatible withMunifax to San Jose in case the city wants to change to anothercomputer system.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Nissi Technologies Inc. (Product defects, recall, etc.).andO;Product:   Wang Laboratories VS10000 (Minicomputer) (Usage)Munifax (financial software) (Product defects, recall, etc.).andO;Topic:     CaliforniaFinancial SoftwareComputer SystemsSupport ServicesSystem IntegrityOverloadProprietary SystemsSystem SelectionEconomics of ComputingMunicipal GovernmentIntegrated Accounting Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>